1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,865
There are some common issues that make data messy.

2
00:00:02,865 --> 00:00:06,180
Column header is being values rather than variable names.

3
00:00:06,180 --> 00:00:09,030
Multiple variables being stored in one column,

4
00:00:09,030 --> 00:00:12,300
variables being stored in both rows and columns.

5
00:00:12,300 --> 00:00:16,110
Multiple types of observational units being stored in the same table,

6
00:00:16,110 --> 00:00:20,250
and a single observational unit being stored in multiple tables.

7
00:00:20,250 --> 00:00:22,170
Data wranglers can use them as

8
00:00:22,170 --> 00:00:25,215
a basic guidance to figure out whether their data is messy.

9
00:00:25,215 --> 00:00:28,440
In this section, we'll leverage the same concepts of directed and

10
00:00:28,440 --> 00:00:32,550
non-directive visual assessment for data quality to identify issues with data structure.

11
00:00:32,550 --> 00:00:35,100
Now, let's dive into these problems.

12
00:00:35,100 --> 00:00:38,145
Take a look at this first example of untidy data.

13
00:00:38,145 --> 00:00:41,490
Here, we have the score data for students who took

14
00:00:41,490 --> 00:00:44,920
five tests with the scores ranging from 0-100.

15
00:00:44,920 --> 00:00:47,450
We have the names of the students as the first column

16
00:00:47,450 --> 00:00:50,440
and different ranges of test scores as part of the header.

17
00:00:50,440 --> 00:00:53,610
Within the table, we have how many tests taken by

18
00:00:53,610 --> 00:00:57,645
a student falling within each score range for example,

19
00:00:57,645 --> 00:01:01,250
Amy scored less than 50 marks on one of her tests and scored

20
00:01:01,250 --> 00:01:05,170
between 50-70 marks on four of her other tests.

21
00:01:05,170 --> 00:01:08,165
Notice how the column headers at this dataset are values,

22
00:01:08,165 --> 00:01:10,430
which makes it complicated to understand the data.

23
00:01:10,430 --> 00:01:12,635
Nevertheless, programmatically parse it.

24
00:01:12,635 --> 00:01:16,520
This can easily be detected visually by looking at the header of the table.

25
00:01:16,520 --> 00:01:19,700
Take a look at the right table where the data has been restructured.

26
00:01:19,700 --> 00:01:22,550
We now have three columns: one for the name of the student,

27
00:01:22,550 --> 00:01:24,500
one for each of the test score categories,

28
00:01:24,500 --> 00:01:26,420
and one for the frequency.

29
00:01:26,420 --> 00:01:28,895
Now, take a look at the example on the left,

30
00:01:28,895 --> 00:01:31,100
where we have two columns in our data set that are

31
00:01:31,100 --> 00:01:34,555
supposed to correspond to a student's names and their test scores.

32
00:01:34,555 --> 00:01:37,940
However, notice how in the name column the values

33
00:01:37,940 --> 00:01:40,970
are structured and students names hyphen their age.

34
00:01:40,970 --> 00:01:43,340
Here, we actually have two variables,

35
00:01:43,340 --> 00:01:46,105
name and age, that are being stored in a single column.

36
00:01:46,105 --> 00:01:48,215
If we wanted to access students age,

37
00:01:48,215 --> 00:01:52,955
we would have to do unnecessary parsing of the name column just to get to these values.

38
00:01:52,955 --> 00:01:56,810
We can instead separate out these columns as we see in the right,

39
00:01:56,810 --> 00:02:00,050
so multiple variables are stored in separate columns.

40
00:02:00,050 --> 00:02:02,060
Here's a very simple example of

41
00:02:02,060 --> 00:02:07,060
another common data tidiness issue variables being stored in both rows and columns.

42
00:02:07,060 --> 00:02:09,815
Here we have the student's name, their age,

43
00:02:09,815 --> 00:02:12,200
and some optional tests that they can opt into,

44
00:02:12,200 --> 00:02:13,775
and their test scores.

45
00:02:13,775 --> 00:02:17,570
Notice how the category of tests A, B, C,

46
00:02:17,570 --> 00:02:23,450
or D is stored across the column and the test scores are being stored across rows.

47
00:02:23,450 --> 00:02:26,540
We can also see that there's a number of NA values for

48
00:02:26,540 --> 00:02:30,115
students who decided not to take some of the optional tasks.

49
00:02:30,115 --> 00:02:32,025
Overall pretty confusing.

50
00:02:32,025 --> 00:02:34,820
Let's see one way that we can consolidate this data.

51
00:02:34,820 --> 00:02:37,415
Take a look at the new DataFrame on the bottom.

52
00:02:37,415 --> 00:02:40,280
Now we have student's name and age,

53
00:02:40,280 --> 00:02:43,925
and we now have the test category as a separate column.

54
00:02:43,925 --> 00:02:47,950
We also have the test score for the cases where students did take the test.

55
00:02:47,950 --> 00:02:52,090
We can avoid unnecessary NA values with the score column.

56
00:02:52,090 --> 00:02:55,220
We do see some duplicated grows, for example,

57
00:02:55,220 --> 00:02:58,340
Marc and Naima's name and age are repeated multiple times,

58
00:02:58,340 --> 00:03:01,745
which we may also need to clean during the cleaning stage.

59
00:03:01,745 --> 00:03:04,715
I'd like to introduce a new movie ratings dataset to you,

60
00:03:04,715 --> 00:03:06,440
where we have a couple of columns.

61
00:03:06,440 --> 00:03:10,070
The movie ID corresponding to an ID associated with the movie,

62
00:03:10,070 --> 00:03:12,110
the movie title of a viewer score,

63
00:03:12,110 --> 00:03:13,370
the viewer or in other words,

64
00:03:13,370 --> 00:03:16,510
the reviewer's name, their income, and their age.

65
00:03:16,510 --> 00:03:20,030
Now, the context of this dataset may immediately appear to be confusing.

66
00:03:20,030 --> 00:03:24,305
Here, we're defining the observational unit as an individual movie,

67
00:03:24,305 --> 00:03:27,500
which includes data on its ID, title, and score.

68
00:03:27,500 --> 00:03:31,060
Where is the viewers income and age coming into the picture?

69
00:03:31,060 --> 00:03:35,420
This is a case of multiple types of observational units stored in the same table.

70
00:03:35,420 --> 00:03:37,565
In this case, the viewer's information is

71
00:03:37,565 --> 00:03:40,690
a separate observational unit, the individual viewer.

72
00:03:40,690 --> 00:03:43,650
Let's separate this information into two tables.

73
00:03:43,650 --> 00:03:45,380
On the table on the bottom left,

74
00:03:45,380 --> 00:03:47,885
you can see we kept intact the movie ID,

75
00:03:47,885 --> 00:03:49,960
title, and reviewers core columns.

76
00:03:49,960 --> 00:03:54,005
On the right table, we have information about our viewer as the observational unit,

77
00:03:54,005 --> 00:03:56,555
including their name, income, and age.

78
00:03:56,555 --> 00:04:00,965
If we ever want to merge the two tables again for easier access to this information,

79
00:04:00,965 --> 00:04:03,745
we can do so using the movie ID key.

80
00:04:03,745 --> 00:04:06,190
Take a look at the two data tables on the screen.

81
00:04:06,190 --> 00:04:08,705
The left one contains information on a movie,

82
00:04:08,705 --> 00:04:10,565
it's ID and the viewer's name.

83
00:04:10,565 --> 00:04:12,140
The table on the right,

84
00:04:12,140 --> 00:04:13,760
also contains the movies ID,

85
00:04:13,760 --> 00:04:16,640
but with columns corresponding to the review and rating.

86
00:04:16,640 --> 00:04:18,485
At times when gathering data,

87
00:04:18,485 --> 00:04:20,855
data may be split into many tables.

88
00:04:20,855 --> 00:04:23,900
Just visually we can see here then we would be much more

89
00:04:23,900 --> 00:04:27,490
simpler if both tables were combined using the ID key.

90
00:04:27,490 --> 00:04:29,750
We could get all the information about

91
00:04:29,750 --> 00:04:35,580
the individual movies i. e our observational unit in a single table.

